  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 2,
      1867, p. 26: "Ephippus, of Athens,was a comic poet of the Middle Comedy, as we learn from the
      testimonies of Suidas....and Antiochus of Alexadria...."</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Ephippus, writer of Middle Comedy, of whose plays
      twelve titles (28 fragments in total) survive. On the basis of historical references, his
      active period can be narrowed down to the years 375-340 BC [2. 197]; c. 370 victory at the
      Lenaea [1. test. 2]. His plays are in part mythological; but there is also a Sapph&#x1E53; (fr.
      20Ephippus, fr. 20) and a Phil&#xFD;ra (fr. 21Ephippus, fr. 21, probably a hetaera play)...."
      B&#xE4;bler, Balbina (G&#xF6;ttingen). "Ephippus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by:
      Hubert Cancik and Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2009. Brill Online.</mads:note>
